          "And Heba of Kemet stood alone in the middle of the empty throne room, a merchant's daughter and the Fifth Judgment, free of debt and full of grief, with a jackal leaning on one leg and a sorcerer's hand on her shoulder and, ranked along every wall, forty crocodiles who were not going anywhere, because divine law had a new address now, and they knew it.",
          "The lie was born within a week. Lies are quick. That is their whole advantage.",
          "Ten thousand people had watched their perfect royal family stand on the river stairs at sunset. Then the family was gone - all of them, in one morning, behind sealed doors, and the only one who walked out was the strange girl with the scale. Kemet needed a story it could carry, and the truth was too heavy, so the market did what markets do.",
          "The priestess betrayed them, said the fruit stalls. They took her in, and she murdered them when they needed her most, said the wine houses. Witch, said the years.",
          "Heba heard every word of it, every year, for the rest of her life. She never corrected it once.",
          "\"Why?\" Fashad demanded, the summer he was twelve, hauling limestone up the western plot with his skinny arms shaking. \"You could tell them! You could make them believe - \"",
          "\"Some doors,\" Heba said, \"should not be gossiped about. Hand me the chisel.\"",
          "She built the house Ahmose had dreamed. White limestone, polished until it held the light. Rows of small square windows cut high in the walls, so the sun fell through in shapes on the floor and even the light came in as a student. Sandalwood and frankincense, always burning. Scrolls in every tongue on open shelves, her Greek stone copied a hundred times, and no guard at the outer door, ever, and any child of any people welcome at the tables - Fashad's pickpocket friends, the river girl's soldiers, Ramek children learning to read their own history in a room that owed them.",
          "Only the inner door was different.",
          "It stood at the bottom, below the reading rooms, at the end of a corridor of white stone, and behind it, in the dark, on a plinth, rested a black sarcophagus with a scale carved on its lid and a thin white line around its seam. Heba fitted the door herself. She bolted seven copper locks down its left side, one below the other, with her father's tools, and she never told anyone what the seven were for, and when Fashad asked she said, \"Inventory,\" and when Mata asked she said nothing, and Mata nodded, because Mata knew that some ledgers are kept closed on purpose.",
          "Every year, on the night the flood arrived, Heba went down the white corridor alone with a lamp and a honey cake, and sat with her back against the door, and told the dark everything - the library's new scrolls, Fashad's marriage, the price of cabbage, the ships from Meluha she still checked, one by one, for a seed-collector who had not yet come home.",
